newsitem.title: AUSTRALIA: RTRS-SFE wheat dampened by cautious trade.
newsitem.headline: RTRS-SFE wheat dampened by cautious trade.

text.p: Trading in both wheat futures and options drifted on Thursday as potential players continued to hold their cards close to the chest.
One trader who did not wish to be named said many potential traders were holding bids and offers out of the market as a result of excessive caution.
"They're worried if someone sees their bid ... people should just put their bids and offers into the market and that's how it starts trading," he said.
Eleven futures trades took place on Thursday, all in the January contract which fell by A$2.50 to A$190.00 on the sale.
Five call options traded, all also in January 1997, one in the A$200 contract at a A$7.50 premium, the others in the A$205 contract at a premium of A$6.00.
Ben Suttie of C A & L Bell Commodities Corp Pty Ltd said he had more sellers than buyers and viewed the Australian market as "a bit overdone and likely to come off further".
Chicago looked bearish short-term but bullish longer-term with US$5.00 a bushel expected by the end of the crop season, he said.
Suttie said he was recommending that producers sell into the cash market in Australia and buy call options in Chicago.
